285[436];304[189-193{The verbs 'to go' and 'to come' in the Brittonic languages have suppletive paradigms. The finite forms ar based on the stems a- < *ag- < *h₂eg̑- 'to drive' and el- < *pelh₂- 'to approach'. In the paradigm of 'to go', these forms are used uncompounded, while in the paradigm of 'to come', they contain the preverb *tu-. In Middle Welsh, some Imoerative forms are based on *ret-e/o- <*ret- 'to run'. The verbal nouns of 'to come' Welsh mynet, Breton monet originate from PIE *menH- 'to step, to stamp' (?). The verbal noun of 'to go', Breton donet contains the same root prefixed with *tu-, i.e. *de-vonet, cf. also Old Breton diminet. The Welsh verbal noun dyfod 'to come' contains *tu- + bod 'to be' based on PIE *bʰweh₂- 'to become, to grow'.  }]

249[{Proto Slavic seems to have two synonyms for the meaning 'name': *jьmę, *jьmene and *měno, měna. Derksen puts their reflexes in modern Slavic languages together as reflexes of IE *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥  with any explanaition. Polish has (and had) both of them ('imię', 'miano') and this alone makes the assumption of a common etymology very doubtfull. There is no phonetic possibility to generate the Polish words from the single Proto-Slavic *jьmę, *jьmene (it is equally impossible to generate the Proto Slavic words from the single IE *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥  phonetically). Therefore Slavic/Polish etymologists keep *jьmę and *měno apart from each other (e.g. Boryś 2005). Upper Sorbian mjeno and Slovak meno, although superficially very similar to Polish miano, are reflexes of *jьmę (or, more precisely, of its forms). The problem with Kashubian is that 'miono' can not be traced directly to Proto-Slavic *měno (we would expect here the same form as in Polish: **'miano'). The explanation is that the original *měno was contaminated by -e- from *jьmene. For now the Kashubian word should be put into a separate cognate class. The problem should be, however, studied closer.}]
